[Deal "S:Q94.AJ63.A72.K64 J75.T54.K93.Q985 KT2.KQ982.854.A3 A863.7.QJT6.JT72"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
1C pass 1H pass 2H pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "39b8aaddaf4aeacb4cbb540f0969d04d9175ac66f3d33b4c486754f4beeba3dd"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/elimination_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{North is to play 4\H. East leads the \DQ.  

You have two \D losers that you can't escape, as well as the \SA. So you must arrange your play so you don't lose a trick to the \SJ. That could mean you will finesse one defender for that card, but it would be a lot better if you could make the defense play \Ss first.

There is no reason to hold up so take your \DA and pull trumps, West showing up with three of them.

Now eliminate \Cs by playing \CA, \CK, and ruffing a \C.

The stage is now set for the throw-in. Be <b>SURE</b> to lead a \D for the throw-in, not a \S.

The defense will win the \D and can then take another \D trick if they like. But then they will have to play a \S (or give you a ruff-sluff). And as long as they start the \Ss you are assured that you will lose only one \S trick, the \SA.

Assume East is on lead for the first \S play.

If he leads the \SA it sets up both the \SK and \SQ so you only have one \S loser. If he leads low you also play low from dummy and West must play the \SJ to prevent you getting a trick with the \ST. Again you only lose one \S.

If West makes the first play by leading a low \S you play low from your hand. East must go up with the \SA to stop you from getting a trick with dummy's \S9. Then your \SK and \SQ will win two tricks.}
[Play "W"]DQ

[Event ""]
