pass 1D 1H 2H X 6D pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "e126a649de863297a90bdfd2cb656f86eb2e352a0ff742817d2369ca71f0ec86"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/elimination_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{West's 2\H bid showed a hand with limit raise or better in \Ds. East doesn't bother with Blackwood since he already knows about the Aces. He just bids the slam. East plays 6\D. South leads the \HK, won by you with the \HA.

The good news is that you have no losers in \Ss, \H, or \Ds. The bad news is that you have two losers in \Cs. The good news is that missing the \C K Q you could try two finesses. The bad news is that South overcalled, so he probably has both honors. The best news of all is that you know how to pull off an elimination play!. Play a trump to dummy's \DK (South discards a \H) and ruff the \H5.

Pull the outstanding trump with the \DA, then play \SA, \SK and ruff a \S.

You want to play the first \C from dummy, so enter dummy with a trump.

Play the \CT from dummy and let it ride if North does not produce the \CQ or \CK. South will win with one of the honors but will have to return another \C or give you a ruff-sluff.

When you are missing the K Q of a suit, as in the \Cs on this hand, taking two finesses gives you a 75% chance of success - <b>all things being equal</b>.  

In this case though, South's overcall means all things are not equal, so your chances are lower than 75%.

But never mind the percentages for a finesse, the end-play was a sure thing.}
[Play "W"]HK

